{"actual_usd":0.156585,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":218,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30663,"reply":"\"I don't think the Christian faith can survive as a mere symbol there.\" *I rest a thumb in the thin pages of my Bible and glance out across the bright square a moment, like I'm looking for the plainest way to say it.* \"If Easter only means renewal in some general poetic sense, then Paul wouldn't have talked the way he did — he'd have said the story still inspires us. But he says if Christ has not been raised, our faith is vain.\"\n\n*I shift on the bench, the wood warm already where the sun's found it.* \"So yes — for Christianity, it requires something to have really happened. Not just a moving idea. A real death, and then a real risen Lord, which means the tomb was not still holding Him. The symbol matters too, of course. New life, hope, all of that. But in Christian faith the meaning rides on the event, not the other way around.\"\n\n\"What are you actually pressing on there — history, theology, or whether faith can ask a modern man to believe a thing that concrete?\"","rolling_24h_usd":90.93634,"run_id":"16d4ae1e-0d6f-4157-96af-44e634115d98"}
